[1]
Date: Mon 19 Apr 2004 1:29 PM
From: Joseph Dudley <jdudley@intellibridge.com>
Source: Press Trust of India 18 Apr 2004 [edited]
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/2004/Apr/18/181_692102,0008.htm>

21 persons, including 2 children and 10 women, have fallen ill reportedly
due to anthrax in certain localities of Murshidabad district in West
Bengal, a senior health officer claimed today.
While 5 persons were diagnosed as reportedly having the disease today [18
Apr 2004], 16 others were diagnosed yesterday in Shibnagar, Bhagirathpur
and Ghatpara localities, Chief Medical Officer of Health Dr Sachhidananda
Sarkar said after visiting the affected villages.
The disease was believed to have been caused after consumption of meat of a
sick cattle a few days back, Sarkar said, adding the medical team has
collected samples from the affected areas.
The villagers have been advised not to consume meat of any sick cattle, he
said. An 8-year-old child and another 10-year-old are among those affected
by the disease, he added.
7 persons had fallen sick in adjoining Dangapara village in Domkal police
station area months back, the CMO said.
--
